You are, of course, entitled to that opinion.  And the rest of the world is entitled to judge you as a jackass based on illiterate rantings that include bad spelling, punctuation, and grammar.<br>
<br>
When you speak to someone, over the telephone or face-to-face, the listener has the advantage of hearing your voice inflection or even seeing your body language.  That non-verbal communication carries information that augments what you are saying.  It also goes far to smooth over errors in grammar.<br>
<br>
When you write, all you are is contained in the words you put down.  If you put down a series of misspelled alphabet jumbles with limited or no grammar applied, you present the appearance of:<br>
<br>
- Someone who doesn't speak English as a first language; or<br>
- Someone who is uneducated; or<br>
- Someone who just doesn't care enough about what they are writing to make it worth reading.<br>
<br>
If you don't speak English as a first language, most thinking people will cut a lot of slack over your writing skills.  Those of us who have tried to master multiple languages know how difficult it is, and will appreciate the fact that you've made the effort.<br>
<br>
The last two points are the critical ones.  Bad writing makes the writer look uneducated and unimportant.  If you couldn't take the time to run a spell check, why should I take the time to read your opinion?  The purpose of writing is to convey information, and if you don't spell properly and you don't use half-decent grammar, you are NOT conveying information.<br>
<br>
I'm not talking about typographical errors either (although a spell checker will pick most of them up).  We've all typed &quot;teh&quot; instead of &quot;the&quot;.  That happens, and it's easy to overlook.  &quot;Your an @#%$!&quot; is not a typographical error (nor will it be picked up on a spell check), it is bad grammar and the writer should know better.  When I see that style of terrible writing, I discount what the writer has to say as unimportant - their message wasn't important enough to put a few seconds thought into the writing, so it must not be important enough for me to spend any time reading.  Nor am I talking about using absolutely formal grammar in an informal writing forum.  MT message boards aren't supposed to be Shakespeare, but they should look better than a community bulletin at an Alabama trailer park.<br>
<br>
